Before continuing to the universal property of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ and the classification theorem we discuss some topological properties of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$.

\begin{prop}[\cite{BaSpec}*{Proposition~2.9}]
Let ${\mathsf{P}} \in {\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$. The closure of ${\mathsf{P}}$ is
\begin{displaymath}
\overline{\{{\mathsf{P}}\}} = \{{\mathsf{Q}}\in {\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}} \; \vert \; {\mathsf{Q}}{\subseteq} {\mathsf{P}}\}.
\end{displaymath}
In particular, ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ is $T_0$ i.e., for ${\mathsf{P}}_1,{\mathsf{P}}_2 \in {\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$
\begin{displaymath}
\overline{\{{\mathsf{P}}_1\}} = \overline{\{{\mathsf{P}}_2\}} \; {\Rightarrow} \; {\mathsf{P}}_1 = {\mathsf{P}}_2.
\end{displaymath}
\end{prop}
\begin{proof}
Let $S_0 = {\mathsf{K}}\setminus {\mathsf{P}}$ denote the complement of ${\mathsf{P}}$. It is immediate that ${\mathsf{P}} \in Z(S_0)$ and one easily checks that if ${\mathsf{P}}\in Z(S)$ then $S{\subseteq} S_0$. Thus for any such $S$ we have $Z(S_0){\subseteq} Z(S)$, i.e.\ $Z(S_0)$ is the smallest closed subset containing ${\mathsf{P}}$. This shows
\begin{displaymath}
\overline{\{{\mathsf{P}}\}} = Z(S_0) = \{{\mathsf{Q}}\in {\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}} \; \vert \; {\mathsf{Q}}{\subseteq} {\mathsf{P}}\}
\end{displaymath}
as claimed. The assertion that ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ is $T_0$ follows immediately.
\end{proof}

\begin{rem}\label{rem_gymnastics}
This proposition is the first indication of the mental gymnastics that occur when dealing with ${\operatorname{Spc}} {\mathsf{K}}$ versus ${\operatorname{Spec}} R$ for a commutative ring $R$. A wealth of further information on the relationship between prime ideals in $R$ and prime tensor-ideals in ${\operatorname{Spc}} {\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{perf}(R)$ can be found in \cite{BaSSS}.
\end{rem}

In fact ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ is much more than just a $T_0$ space.

\begin{defn}\label{defn_spectral}
A topological space $X$ is a \emph{spectral space} if it verifies the following properties:
\begin{itemize}
\item[(1)] $X$ is $T_0$;
\item[(2)] $X$ is quasi-compact;
\item[(3)] the quasi-compact open subsets of $X$ are closed under finite intersections and form an open basis of $X$;
\item[(4)] every non-empty irreducible closed subset of $X$ has a generic point.
\end{itemize}
Given spectral spaces $X$ and $Y$, a \emph{spectral map} $f\colon X{\longrightarrow} Y$ is a continuous map such that for any quasi-compact open $U{\subseteq} Y$ the preimage $f^{-1}(U)$ is quasi-compact. 
\end{defn}

Typical examples of spectral spaces are given by ${\operatorname{Spec}} R$ where $R$ is a commutative ring. In fact Hochster has shown in \cite{HochsterSpectral} that any spectral topological space is of this form. Further examples include the topological space underlying any quasi-compact and quasi-separated scheme. Another class of examples is provided by the following result.

\begin{thm}[\cite{BKS}]\label{thm_spectral}
Let ${\mathsf{K}}$ be as above. The space ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ is spectral.
\end{thm}

Thus the spaces we produce by taking spectra of tensor triangulated categories are particularly nice and enjoy many desirable properties.

\begin{aside}
There is a deep connection between spectral spaces and the theory of particularly nice lattices (coherent frames to be precise). One consequence of this is that the topology of a spectral space is determined by the specialisation ordering on points. This ordering is given by defining, for a spectral space $X$, a point $y\in X$ to be a specialisation of $x\in X$ if $y$ is in the closure of $x$. Viewed through the lens of lattice theory, the key fact which makes Balmer's theory work so well is that the lattice of thick tensor-ideals is distributive. More details on this point of view can be found in \cite{KockPitsch}.
\end{aside}

As a complement to Theorem~\ref{thm_spectral} let us record a few related facts which appear in Balmer's work.

\begin{prop}\label{prop_spc_props}
For any rigid tensor triangulated category ${\mathsf{K}}$ the following assertions hold.
\begin{itemize}
\item[$(a)$] Any non-empty closed subset of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ contains at least one closed point.
\item[$(b)$] For any $k\in {\mathsf{K}}$ the open subset $U(k) = {\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}} \setminus {\operatorname{supp}}(k)$ is quasi-compact.
\item[$(c)$] Any quasi-compact open subset of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ is of the form $U(k)$ for some $k\in {\mathsf{K}}$.
\end{itemize}
\end{prop}
\begin{proof}
Both results can be found in \cite{BaSpec}: the first is Corollary~2.12, and the second two are the content of Proposition~2.14.
\end{proof}

In particular, it follows from the above proposition and Lemma~\ref{lem_supp_props} that the $U(k)$ for $k\in {\mathsf{K}}$ give a basis of quasi-compact open subsets for ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ that is closed under finite intersections as is required in the definition of a spectral space.

\begin{rem}\label{rem_noeth}
Recall, or prove as an exercise, that a space is noetherian (i.e.\ satisfies the descending chain condition for closed subsets) if and only if every open subset is quasi-compact. Combining this with (c) above we see that if ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$ is noetherian then every open subset is of the form $U(k)$ for some $k\in {\mathsf{K}}$ and hence every closed subset is the support of some object.
\end{rem}



\subsection{The classification theorem}

We now come to the first main result of these notes, namely the abstract classification of thick tensor-ideals of ${\mathsf{K}}$ in terms of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$. The starting point to this story is an abstract axiomatisation of the properties of the support, based on Lemma~\ref{lem_supp_props}.

\begin{defn}
A \emph{support data} on $({\mathsf{K}},\otimes,\mathbf{1})$ is a pair $(X,\sigma)$ where $X$ is a topological space and $\sigma$ is an assignment associating to each object $k$ of ${\mathsf{K}}$ a closed subset $\sigma(k)$ of $X$ such that:
\begin{itemize}
\item[$(a)$] $\sigma(\mathbf{1}) = X$ and $\sigma(0) = \varnothing$;
\item[$(b)$] $\sigma(k\oplus l) = \sigma(k) \cup \sigma(l)$;
\item[$(c)$] $\sigma({\Sigma} k) = \sigma(k)$;
\item[$(d)$] for any distinguished triangle
\begin{displaymath}
k {\longrightarrow} l {\longrightarrow} m {\longrightarrow} {\Sigma} k
\end{displaymath}
in ${\mathsf{K}}$ there is a containment 
\begin{displaymath}
\sigma(l) {\subseteq} (\sigma(k) \cup \sigma(m));
\end{displaymath}
\item[$(e)$] $\sigma(k\otimes l) = \sigma(k) \cap \sigma(l)$.
\end{itemize}
A \emph{morphism of support data} $f\colon (X,\sigma) {\longrightarrow} (Y,\tau)$ on ${\mathsf{K}}$ is a continuous map $f\colon X{\longrightarrow} Y$ such that for every $k\in {\mathsf{K}}$ the equality
\begin{displaymath}
\sigma(k) = f^{-1}(\tau(k))
\end{displaymath}
is satisfied. An isomorphism of support data is a morphism $f$ of support data where $f$ is a homeomorphism.
\end{defn}

It should, given the definition of the support, come as no surprise that the pair $({\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}, {\operatorname{supp}})$ is a universal support data for ${\mathsf{K}}$.

\begin{thm}[\cite{BaSpec}*{Theorem~3.2}]
Let ${\mathsf{K}}$ be as throughout. The pair $({\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}, {\operatorname{supp}})$ is the terminal support data on ${\mathsf{K}}$. Explicitly, given any support data $(X,\sigma)$ on ${\mathsf{K}}$ there is a unique morphism of support data $f\colon (X,\sigma) {\longrightarrow} ({\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}, {\operatorname{supp}})$, i.e.\ a unique continuous map $f$ such that
\begin{displaymath}
\sigma(k) = f^{-1}{\operatorname{supp}}(k)
\end{displaymath}
for all $k\in {\mathsf{K}}$. This unique morphism is given by sending $x\in X$ to
\begin{displaymath}
f(x) = \{k\in {\mathsf{K}}\; \vert \; x\notin \sigma(k)\}.
\end{displaymath}
\end{thm}
\begin{proof}[Sketch of proof]
We give a brief sketch of the argument. We have seen in Lemma~\ref{lem_supp_props} that the pair $({\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}, {\operatorname{supp}})$ is in fact a support data for ${\mathsf{K}}$. By the same lemma it is clear that for $x\in X$ the full subcategory $f(x)$, defined as in the statement, is a proper thick tensor-ideal: it is proper by (a), closed under summands by (b), closed under ${\Sigma}$ by (c), closed under extensions by (d), and a tensor-ideal by (e). To see that it is prime suppose $k\otimes l$ lies in $f(x)$. By axiom (e) for a support data we have
\begin{displaymath}
x\notin \sigma(k\otimes l) = \sigma(k)\cap \sigma(l).
\end{displaymath}
and hence $x$ must fail to lie in at least one of $\sigma(k), \sigma(l)$ implying that one of $k$ or $l$ lies in $f(x)$.

The map $f$ is a map of support data as $f(x)\in {\operatorname{supp}} k$ if and only if $k\notin f(x)$ if and only if $x\in \sigma(k)$, i.e.\
\begin{displaymath}
f^{-1}{\operatorname{supp}}(k) = \{x\in X\; \vert \; f(x)\in {\operatorname{supp}} k\} = \{x\in X\; \vert \; x\in \sigma(k)\} = \sigma(k).
\end{displaymath}
This also proves continuity of $f$ by definition of the Zariski topology on ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$. We leave the unicity of $f$ to the reader (or it can be found as \cite{BaSpec}*{Lemma~3.3}).
\end{proof}

Before stating the promised classification theorem we need one more definition (we also provide two bonus definitions which will be useful both here and later).

\begin{defn}\label{defn_thomason}
Let $X$ be a spectral space and let $W {\subseteq} X$ be a subset of $X$. We say $W$ is \emph{specialisation closed} if for any $w\in W$ and $w' \in \overline{\{w\}}$ we have $w'\in W$. That is, $W$ is specialisation closed if it is the union of the closures of its elements. Given $w,w'$ as above we call $w'$ a \emph{specialisation} of $w$. Dually, we say $W$ is \emph{generisation closed} if given any $w' \in W$ and a $w\in X$ such that $w'\in \overline{\{w\}}$ then we have $w\in W$. In this situation we call $w$ a \emph{generisation} of $w'$.

A \emph{Thomason subset} of $X$ is a subset of the form
\begin{displaymath}
\bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} V_\lambda
\end{displaymath}
where each $V_\lambda$ is a closed subset of $X$ with quasi-compact complement. Note that any Thomason subset is specialisation closed. We denote by ${\operatorname{Thom}}(X)$ the collection of Thomason subsets of $X$. It is a poset with respect to inclusion and in fact also carries the structure of a complete lattice where the join is given by taking unions.
\end{defn}

\begin{rem}\label{rem_noeth_spec}
As observed in Remark~\ref{rem_noeth} if $X$ is noetherian then every open subset is quasi-compact. Thus the Thomason subsets of $X$ are precisely the specialisation closed subsets.
\end{rem}

\begin{rem}
By Proposition~\ref{prop_spc_props} for any $k\in {\mathsf{K}}$ the subset ${\operatorname{supp}}(k)$ is a Thomason subset of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$, as is any union of supports of objects. Part (c) of the same proposition implies the converse, namely that any Thomason subset $V$ can be written as a union of supports of objects of $k$. This observation explains the role of Thomason subsets in the following theorem.
\end{rem}



\begin{thm}[\cite{BaSpec}*{Theorem~4.10}]\label{thm_spc_class}
The assignments
\begin{displaymath}
\sigma\colon {\operatorname{Thick}}^\otimes({\mathsf{K}}) {\longrightarrow} {\operatorname{Thom}}({\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}), \;\; \sigma({\mathsf{I}}) = \bigcup_{k\in {\mathsf{I}}} {\operatorname{supp}}(k)
\end{displaymath}
and
\begin{displaymath}
\tau\colon {\operatorname{Thom}}({\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}) {\longrightarrow} {\operatorname{Thick}}^\otimes({\mathsf{K}}), \;\; \tau(V) = \{k\in {\mathsf{K}}\; \vert \; {\operatorname{supp}}(k){\subseteq} V\},
\end{displaymath}
for ${\mathsf{I}} \in {\operatorname{Thick}}^\otimes({\mathsf{K}})$ and $V\in {\operatorname{Thom}}({\mathsf{K}})$ give an isomorphism of lattices
\begin{displaymath}
{\operatorname{Thick}}^\otimes({\mathsf{K}}) \cong {\operatorname{Thom}}({\mathsf{K}}).
\end{displaymath}
\end{thm}
\begin{proof}[Sketch of proof]
By the previous remark and the properties of the support given in Lemma~\ref{lem_supp_props} both assignments are well defined, i.e.\ $\sigma({\mathsf{I}})$ is a Thomason subset and $\tau(V)$ is a thick tensor-ideal. It is clear that both morphisms are inclusion preserving, so we just need to check that they are inverse to one another.

Consider the thick tensor-ideal $\tau\sigma({\mathsf{I}})$. It is clear that ${\mathsf{I}}{\subseteq} \tau\sigma({\mathsf{I}})$. The equality is proved by showing that
\begin{displaymath}
{\mathsf{I}} = \bigcap_{\substack{{\mathsf{P}}\in {\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}} \\ {\mathsf{I}}{\subseteq} {\mathsf{P}}}} {\mathsf{P}} = \tau\sigma({\mathsf{I}}).
\end{displaymath}
We refer to \cite{BaSpec} for the details.

On the other hand consider the Thomason subset $\sigma\tau(V)$. In this case it is clear that $\sigma\tau(V){\subseteq} V$. By the remark preceding the theorem we know $V$ can be written as a union of supports of objects and so this containment is in fact an equality.


\end{proof}

\begin{aside}
By Stone duality the lattice ${\operatorname{Thom}}({\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}})$ actually determines ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$. So by the theorem if we know ${\operatorname{Thick}}^\otimes({\mathsf{K}})$ we can recover ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$. In fact this gives another way of describing the universality of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{K}}$.
\end{aside}

To conclude we briefly explain what the spectrum is in each of our current running examples and then give a slightly more detailed treatment of a particular case.

\begin{ex}\label{ex_ringspec}
Let $R$ be a commutative ring. Then
\begin{displaymath}
{\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{perf}(R) \cong {\operatorname{Spec}} R.
\end{displaymath}
This computation is due to Neeman \cite{NeeChro} (and Hopkins) in the case that $R$ is noetherian and Thomason \cite{Thomclass} in general. Applying the above theorem, in combination with Lemma~\ref{lem_small_unit_gen}, tells us that thick subcategories of ${\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{perf}(R)$ are in bijection with Thomason subsets of ${\operatorname{Spec}} R$.
\end{ex}

\begin{ex}
As previously let $\mathrm{SH}^\mathrm{fin}$ denote the finite stable homotopy category. The description of the thick subcategories of $\mathrm{SH}^\mathrm{fin}$ by Devinatz, Hopkins, and Smith \cite{DevinatzHopkinsSmith} allows one to compute ${\operatorname{Spc}}\mathrm{SH}^\mathrm{fin}$. A nice picture of this space can be found in \cite{BaSSS}*{Corollary~9.5}.
\end{ex}

\begin{ex}
Let $G$ be a finite group and $k$ a field whose characteristic divides the order of $G$. By a result of Benson, Carlson, and Rickard \cite{BCR} we have
\begin{displaymath}
{\operatorname{Spc}}{\operatorname{\underline{{\operatorname{mod}}} kG \cong {\operatorname{Proj}} H^\bullet(G;k)
\end{displaymath}
i.e.\ the spectrum of the stable category is the space underlying the projective scheme associated to the group cohomology ring.
\end{ex}

\subsection{An explicit example}
We now describe, in some detail but mostly without proofs, the explicit example of ${\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$, the bounded derived category of finitely generated abelian groups. Our aim is to highlight some of the phenomena involved in studying the spectrum rather than to give a proof of the classification in this case.

As ${\mathbb{Z}}$ is a hereditary ring, i.e.\ has global dimension $1$, every complex $E\in {\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$ is formal. Explicitly, this means that for every $E$ there is an isomorphism
\begin{displaymath}
E\cong \bigoplus_{i\in {\mathbb{Z}}} \Sigma^{-i}H^i(E).
\end{displaymath}
Thus to understand tensor-ideals in ${\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$ it is sufficient to understand what happens to finitely generated abelian groups. 

Recall from Lemma~\ref{lem_small_unit_gen} that since ${\mathbb{Z}}$ generates ${\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$ every thick subcategory is a tensor-ideal. Our first observation is that if $p\neq q$ are distinct primes in ${\mathbb{Z}}$ then
\begin{displaymath}
{\mathbb{Z}}/p{\mathbb{Z}} \otimes^\mathbf{L}_{\mathbb{Z}} {\mathbb{Z}}/q{\mathbb{Z}} \cong 0.
\end{displaymath}
If ${\mathsf{P}}$ is a prime tensor-ideal then it certainly contains $0$. This observation then shows that ${\mathsf{P}}$ must contain ${\mathbb{Z}}/p{\mathbb{Z}}$ for all but possibly one prime $p\in {\mathbb{Z}}$. In fact, this missing prime (or lack thereof) completely determines the prime tensor-ideal: the homeomorphism
\begin{displaymath}
\phi\colon {\operatorname{Spec}} {\mathbb{Z}} {\longrightarrow} {\operatorname{Spc}} {\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})
\end{displaymath}
can be described explicitly as
\begin{displaymath}
\phi((p)) = {\operatorname{thick}}({\mathbb{Z}}/q{\mathbb{Z}}\;\vert\; q\neq p).
\end{displaymath}
In particular, $\phi$ sends the $0$ ideal to the thick subcategory consisting of all complexes with torsion cohomology, which is the maximal proper thick subcategory of ${\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$. As this maximal proper thick subcategory certainly contains $\phi((p))$ for all $p\neq 0$ it does indeed give the generic point of ${\operatorname{Spc}} {\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$ under the Zariski topology.

On the other hand $\phi^{-1}$ sends a prime tensor-ideal ${\mathsf{P}}$ to
\begin{displaymath}
\phi^{-1}({\mathsf{P}}) = \{n\in {\mathbb{Z}} \; \vert \; {\operatorname{cone}}({\mathbb{Z}} \stackrel{n}{\longrightarrow}{\mathbb{Z}})\notin {\mathsf{P}}\},
\end{displaymath}
which one can check is really a prime ideal.

This gives a concrete illustration of the reversal of inclusions (noted in Remark~\ref{rem_gymnastics}) upon passing from prime ideals in ${\mathbb{Z}}$ to prime tensor-ideals in ${\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$. To localise at a prime ideal $(p)\in {\mathbb{Z}}$ we simply invert those elements in ${\mathbb{Z}}\setminus (p)$. On the other hand, in ${\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$, we invert these elements by killing their cones, i.e.\ taking the quotient by $\phi((p))$. The analogue is true for general commutative rings\textemdash{}localising at a smaller prime ideal inverts more elements and thus the corresponding thick subcategory in the perfect complexes is larger.

One can also use this example to gain further intuition for the support and to somewhat explain the motivation behind defining it in terms of failure to lie in prime tensor-ideals. There is an equivalence, up to idempotent completion, for each prime $p\in {\mathbb{Z}}$
\begin{displaymath}
{\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})/\phi((p)) {{\longrightarrow}} {\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}}_{(p)})
\end{displaymath}
and one can identify, under this functor, the projection
\begin{displaymath}
{\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}}) \stackrel\pi{\longrightarrow} {\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})/\phi((p))
\end{displaymath}
with localisation at $(p)$. Thus, for $E\in {\mathsf{D}}^\mathrm{b}({\mathbb{Z}})$, we have $\phi((p)) \in {\operatorname{supp}} E$ if and only if $\pi(E)\neq 0$ if and only if $E_{(p)} \neq 0$. This identifies the abstract support with the usual homological support of complexes.

\section{Generalised Rickard idempotents and supports}

In this section we use the Balmer spectrum to construct a theory of supports for triangulated categories admitting arbitrary set-indexed coproducts (so being interesting and essentially small become mutually exclusive). Our main reference is \cite{BaRickard} and again, we follow it relatively closely.

\subsection{Rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated categories}

We start by introducing the main players of this section, rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated categories. In order to define such a creature it makes sense to start with the notion of a compactly generated triangulated category.

\begin{defn}
Let ${\mathsf{T}}$ be a triangulated category admitting all set-indexed coproducts. We say an object $t\in {\mathsf{T}}$ is \emph{compact} if ${\mathsf{T}}(t,-)$ preserves arbitrary coproducts, i.e.\ if for any family $\{X_\lambda \; \vert \; \lambda \in \Lambda\}$ of objects in ${\mathsf{T}}$ the natural morphism
\begin{displaymath}
\bigoplus_{\lambda \in \Lambda} {\mathsf{T}}(t, X_\lambda) {\longrightarrow} {\mathsf{T}}(t, \coprod_{\lambda \in \Lambda} X_\lambda)
\end{displaymath}
is an isomorphism.

We say ${\mathsf{T}}$ is \emph{compactly generated} if there is a set $G$ of compact objects of ${\mathsf{T}}$ such that an object $X\in {\mathsf{T}}$ is zero if and only if
\begin{displaymath}
{\mathsf{T}}(g, {\Sigma}^i X) = 0 \;\; \text{for every} \; g\in G \; \text{and} \; i\in {\mathbb{Z}}.
\end{displaymath}
We denote by ${\mathsf{T}}^c$ the full subcategory of compact objects of ${\mathsf{T}}$ and note that it is an essentially small thick subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$.
\end{defn}

\begin{ex}\label{ex_cg}
Let us give some examples of compactly generated triangulated categories which will be used as illustrations throughout.
\begin{itemize}
\item[(1)] Let $R$ be a ring and denote by ${\mathsf{D}}(R)$ the unbounded derived category of $R$. Then ${\mathsf{D}}(R)$ is compactly generated and $R$ is a compact generator for ${\mathsf{D}}(R)$.
\item[(2)] Let $\mathrm{SH}$ denote the stable homotopy category. The sphere spectrum $S^0$ is a compact generator for $\mathrm{SH}$ and hence it is compactly generated.
\item[(3)] Let $G$ be a finite group and let $k$ be a field whose characteristic divides the order of $G$. Then ${\operatorname{\underline{{\operatorname{Mod}}} kG$, the stable category of aribtrary $kG$-modules is a compactly generated triangulated category.
\end{itemize}
\end{ex}

\begin{defn}
A \emph{compactly generated tensor triangulated category} is a triple $({\mathsf{T}}, \otimes, \mathbf{1})$ where ${\mathsf{T}}$ is a compactly generated triangulated category, and $(\otimes, \mathbf{1})$ is a symmetric monoidal structure on ${\mathsf{T}}$ such that the tensor product $\otimes$ is a coproduct preserving exact functor in each variable and the compact objects ${\mathsf{T}}^c$ form a tensor subcategory. In particular, we require that the unit $\mathbf{1}$ is compact.
\end{defn}

\begin{rem}
We will frequently supress the tensor product and unit and just refer to ${\mathsf{T}}$ as a compactly generated tensor triangulated category.
\end{rem}

\begin{rem}
By Brown representability \cite{NeeGrot}*{Theorem~3.1}, and the assumption that the tensor product is coproduct preserving, it is automatic that ${\mathsf{T}}$ is closed symmetric monoidal\textemdash{}for each $X\in {\mathsf{T}}$ the functor $X\otimes -$ has a right adjoint which we denote by $\hom(X,-)$.
\end{rem}

Finally, we come to the combination of hypotheses that we can get the most mileage out of.

\begin{defn}
A \emph{rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category} ${\mathsf{T}}$ is a compactly generated tensor triangulated category such that the full subcategory ${\mathsf{T}}^c$ of compact objects is rigid. Explicitly, not only is ${\mathsf{T}}^c$ a tensor subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$, but it is closed under the internal hom (which exists by the previous remark) and is rigid in the sense of Definition~\ref{defn_rigid}.
\end{defn}

\begin{ex}
Each of the triangulated categories covered in Example~\ref{ex_cg} (with the proviso in (1) that the ring is commutative) is a rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category via the left derived tensor product, smash product, and tensor product over the ground field with the diagonal action respectively.
\end{ex}


\subsection{Localising sequences and smashing localisations}
We now review some definitions concerning the particular subcategories of a rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category that we will wish to consider. Of course some of the definitions we make are valid more generally, but we will restrict ourselves to what we need. Throughout we fix a rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category ${\mathsf{T}}$.

\begin{defn}
Let ${\mathsf{L}}$ be a triangulated subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$. The subcategory ${\mathsf{L}}$ is \emph{localising} if it is closed under arbitrary coproducts in ${\mathsf{T}}$. Dually, it is \emph{colocalising} if it is closed under arbitrary products in ${\mathsf{T}}$. Put another way, a full subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$ is localising if it is closed under suspensions, cones, and coproducts and colocalising if it is closed under suspensions, cones, and products.

Let ${\mathsf{I}}$ be a localising subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$. We call ${\mathsf{I}}$ a \emph{localising tensor-ideal} if for any $X\in {\mathsf{T}}$ and $Y\in {\mathsf{I}}$ the object $X\otimes Y$ lies in ${\mathsf{I}}$.

Given a family of objects $S{\subseteq} {\mathsf{T}}$ we denote by ${\operatorname{loc}}(S)$ (resp.\ ${\operatorname{loc}}^\otimes(S)$) the smallest localising subcategory (resp.\ localising tensor-ideal) of ${\mathsf{T}}$ containing $S$ and by ${\operatorname{Loc}}({\mathsf{T}})$ (resp.\ ${\operatorname{Loc}}^\otimes({\mathsf{T}})$) the collection of all localising subcategories (resp.\ localising tensor-ideals) of ${\mathsf{T}}$.
\end{defn}

\begin{rem}
There is, \emph{a priori}, no reason that either ${\operatorname{Loc}}({\mathsf{T}})$ or ${\operatorname{Loc}}^\otimes({\mathsf{T}})$ should be sets. In fact, whether or not these collections can form proper classes in the given situation is a longstanding open problem.
\end{rem}

\begin{rem}
By \cite{NeeCat}*{Proposition~1.6.8} every localising subcategory and every colocalising subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$ is automatically closed under direct summands, i.e.\ (co)localising implies thick.
\end{rem}

\begin{rem}\label{rem_gen}
One can show, see for instance \cite{NeeGrot}*{Lemma~3.2}, that a set $G$ of compact objects in ${\mathsf{T}}$ is a set of compact generators for ${\mathsf{T}}$ if and only if ${\operatorname{loc}}(G) = {\mathsf{T}}$.
\end{rem}

This last remark is very important in practice. For instance, it is a key point in proving the following elementary but useful lemma. Perhaps more importantly, the proof illustrates an argument which appears frequently in this subject.

\begin{lem}\label{lem_big_rigid}
Let ${\mathsf{T}}$ be a rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category. Then, for $t\in {\mathsf{T}}^c$ the isomorphism of endofunctors of ${\mathsf{T}}^c$
\begin{displaymath}
t^\vee\otimes (-) \stackrel{{\alpha}}{{\longrightarrow}} \hom(t,-)
\end{displaymath}
extends to an isomorphism of the corresponding endofunctors of ${\mathsf{T}}$. That is, for any $X\in {\mathsf{T}}$ we have $t^\vee\otimes X \cong \hom(t,X)$. In particular, $\hom(t,-)$ preserves coproducts and $t\otimes (-)$ is left and right adjoint to $t^\vee\otimes (-)$ when viewed as endofunctors of ${\mathsf{T}}$.
\end{lem}
\begin{proof}
As in Definition~\ref{defn_rigid} we can define a natural transformation
\begin{displaymath}
{\alpha}\colon t^\vee \otimes (-) {\longrightarrow} \hom(t,-)
\end{displaymath}
of functors ${\mathsf{T}} {\longrightarrow} {\mathsf{T}}$. Define a full subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$ as follows
\begin{displaymath}
{\mathsf{S}} = \{X\in {\mathsf{T}} \; \vert \; {\alpha}_X\colon t^\vee\otimes X {\longrightarrow} \hom(t,X) \; \text{is an isomorphism}\}.
\end{displaymath}
As both functors involved preserve suspensions and coproducts, and ${\alpha}$ is also compatible with suspensions and coproducts, we see that ${\mathsf{S}}$ is closed under coproducts and suspensions. Given a triangle $X{\longrightarrow} Y {\longrightarrow} Z {\longrightarrow} {\Sigma} X$ with $X,Y \in {\mathsf{S}}$ the naturality of ${\alpha}$ guarantees the commutativity of the following diagram
\begin{displaymath}
\xymatrix{
t^\vee\otimes X \ar[r] \ar[d]^-{{\alpha}_X} & t^\vee\otimes Y \ar[r] \ar[d]^-{{\alpha}_Y} & t^\vee\otimes Z \ar[r] \ar[d]^-{{\alpha}_Z} & \Sigma (t^\vee\otimes X) \ar[d]^-{{\alpha}_{\Sigma X}}\\
\hom(t,X) \ar[r] & \hom(t,Y) \ar[r] & \hom(t,Z) \ar[r] & \Sigma\hom(t,X)
}
\end{displaymath}
As both functors are exact the rows are triangles and so since ${\alpha}_X$ and ${\alpha}_Y$ are isomorphisms it follows that ${\alpha}_Z$ must also be an isomorphism and hence $Z\in {\mathsf{S}}$. Thus ${\mathsf{S}}$ is a localising subcategory and, by rigidity of ${\mathsf{T}}^c$, we have ${\mathsf{T}}^c {\subseteq} {\mathsf{S}}$. It then follows from \cite{NeeGrot}*{Lemma~3.2} that ${\mathsf{S}} = {\mathsf{T}}$ which proves the first assertion of the Lemma; the rest of the statements are immediate.
\end{proof}

Another illustration is given by the following analogue of Lemma~\ref{lem_small_unit_gen}.

\begin{lem}\label{lem_big_unit_gen}
Let ${\mathsf{T}}$ be a rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category. If $\mathbf{1}$ is a compact generator for ${\mathsf{T}}$, i.e.\ if ${\mathsf{T}} = {\operatorname{loc}}(\mathbf{1})$, then every localising subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$ is a localising tensor-ideal.
\end{lem}
\begin{proof}
Exercise.
\end{proof}

Localising subcategories are not imaginatively named\textemdash{}they are precisely the kernels of localisation functors. We will only give a brief outline of the formalism that we need and do not go into the details of forming Verdier quotients. There are many excellent sources for further information on this topic such as \cite{NeeCat}, \cite{NeeHolim}, and \cite{KrLoc}.

\begin{defn}\label{defn_locsequence}
A \emph{localisation sequence} is a diagram
\begin{displaymath}
\xymatrix{
{\mathsf{L}} \ar[r]<0.5ex>^-{i_*} \ar@{<-}[r]<-0.5ex>_-{i^!} & {\mathsf{T}} \ar[r]<0.5ex>^-{j^*} \ar@{<-}[r]<-0.5ex>_-{j_*} & {\mathsf{C}}
}
\end{displaymath}
where $i^!$ is right adjoint to $i_*$ and $j_*$ is right adjoint to $j^*$, both $i_*$ and $j_*$ are fully faithful and hence embed ${\mathsf{L}}$ and ${\mathsf{C}}$ as a localising and a colocalising subcategory respectively, and we have equalities
\begin{displaymath}
(i_*{\mathsf{L}})^\perp = j_*{\mathsf{C}} \quad \text{and} \quad {}^\perp(j_*{\mathsf{C}}) = i_*{\mathsf{L}},
\end{displaymath}
where
\begin{displaymath}
(i_*{\mathsf{L}})^\perp = \{Y\in {\mathsf{T}} \; \vert \; {\mathsf{T}}(i_*L, Y) = 0 \;\; \text{for all} \; L\in {\mathsf{L}}\}
\end{displaymath}
and
\begin{displaymath}
{}^\perp(j_*{\mathsf{C}}) = \{Y\in {\mathsf{T}} \; \vert \; {\mathsf{T}}(Y,j_*C) = 0 \;\; \text{for all} \; C\in {\mathsf{C}}\}.
\end{displaymath}
We refer to the composite $i_*i^!$ as the \emph{acyclisation} functor and $j_*j^*$ as the \emph{localisation} functor corresponding to this localisation sequence.

We will frequently abuse the notation in such situations and identify ${\mathsf{L}}$ and ${\mathsf{C}}$ with their images under the fully faithful functors $i_*$ and $j_*$.
\end{defn}

The existence of a localisation sequence provides a great deal of information and has many consequences. The following proposition lists a few of the ones we will need. We suggest perusing the references given before the above definition for more details as well as proofs of the statements made below (there are, in addition, relevant references in \cite{BaRickard}*{Theorem~2.6} where these statements also appear).

\begin{prop}\label{prop_loc_seq}
If we have a localisation sequence as in the definition then the following statements hold.
\begin{itemize}
\item[$(a)$] The composites $j^*i_*$ and $i^!j_*$ are zero. Moreover, the kernel of $j^*$ is precisely ${\mathsf{L}}$.
\item[$(b)$] The composite 
\begin{displaymath}
{\mathsf{C}} \stackrel{j_*}{{\longrightarrow}} {\mathsf{T}} {\longrightarrow} {\mathsf{T}}/{\mathsf{L}}
\end{displaymath}
is an equivalence. In particular, the Verdier quotient ${\mathsf{T}}/{\mathsf{L}}$ is locally small and the canonical projection ${\mathsf{T}} {\longrightarrow} {\mathsf{T}}/{\mathsf{L}}$ has a right adjoint.
\item[$(c)$] For every $X\in {\mathsf{T}}$ there is a distinguished triangle
\begin{displaymath}
i_*i^!X {\longrightarrow} X {\longrightarrow} j_*j^*X {\longrightarrow} {\Sigma} i_*i^!X.
\end{displaymath}
These triangles are functorial and unique in the sense that given any distinguished triangle
\begin{displaymath}
X' {\longrightarrow} X {\longrightarrow} X'' {\longrightarrow} {\Sigma} X \quad \text{with} \; X'\in {\mathsf{L}} \; \text{and} \; X''\in {\mathsf{C}}
\end{displaymath}
there are unique isomorphisms $X' \cong i_*i^!X$ and $X'' \cong j_*j^*X$.
\item[$(d)$] A localisation sequence is completely determined by either of the pairs of adjoint functors $(i_*,i^!)$ or $(j^*,j_*)$.
\end{itemize}
\end{prop}

In nature localising sequences are actually rather easy to come by as a consequence of the following form of Brown representability.

\begin{thm}\label{thm_brown}
Let ${\mathsf{T}}$ be a compactly generated triangulated category, $L{\subseteq} {\mathsf{T}}$ a set of objects, and set ${\mathsf{L}} = {\operatorname{loc}}(L)$. Then the inclusion $i_*\colon {\mathsf{L}} {\longrightarrow} {\mathsf{T}}$ admits a right adjoint. In particular, ${\mathsf{L}}$ fits into a localisation sequence
\begin{displaymath}
\xymatrix{
{\mathsf{L}} \ar[r]<0.5ex>^-{i_*} \ar@{<-}[r]<-0.5ex>_-{i^!} & {\mathsf{T}} \ar[r]<0.5ex>^-{j^*} \ar@{<-}[r]<-0.5ex>_-{j_*} & {\mathsf{T}}/{\mathsf{L}}
}
\end{displaymath}
\end{thm}
\begin{proof}
This follows from the results in Section~7.2 of \cite{KrLoc} combined with \cite{NeeCat}*{Theorem~8.4.4}.
\end{proof}

By definition, given any localisation sequence as above, the functors $i_*$ and $j^*$ preserve coproducts by virtue of being left adjoints. The condition that the right adjoints $i^!$ and $j_*$ also preserve coproducts turns out to be very strong and very useful.

\begin{defn}
A localisation sequence as in Definition~\ref{defn_locsequence} is \emph{smashing} if $i^!$ (or equivalently $j_*$) preserves coproducts. In this case we call ${\mathsf{L}}$ a \emph{smashing subcategory} of ${\mathsf{T}}$. If ${\mathsf{L}}$ is, moreover, a tensor-ideal we call it a \emph{smashing tensor-ideal}.
\end{defn}

In a smashing localisation sequence ${\mathsf{C}}$ is also, under the embedding $j_*$, a localising subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$. The standard source of smashing localisation sequences is the following well known lemma.

\begin{lem}\label{lem_smash}
Let ${\mathsf{T}}$ be a compactly generated triangulated category and $S{\subseteq} {\mathsf{T}}^c$ a set of compact objects. Then ${\mathsf{S}} = {\operatorname{loc}}(S)$ is a smashing subcategory, i.e.\ the inclusion $i_*\colon {\mathsf{S}} {\longrightarrow} {\mathsf{T}}$ admits a coproduct preserving right adjoint $i^!$.
\end{lem}
\begin{proof}
We know from Theorem~\ref{thm_brown} that $i_*$ admits a right adjoint $i^!$. It follows from Thomason's localisation theorem \cite{NeeGrot}*{Theorem~2.1} together with \cite{NeeGrot}*{Theorem~5.1} that $i^!$ preserves coproducts.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Generalised Rickard idempotents and supports}
Throughout this section we will assume ${\mathsf{T}}$ is a rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category such that ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{T}}^c$, the spectrum of the compact objects, is a noetherian topological space. Recall from Remark~\ref{rem_noeth_spec} that in this case the Thomason subsets of ${\operatorname{Spc}}{\mathsf{T}}^c$ are precisely the specialisation closed subsets. 

\begin{aside}
The assumption that ${\operatorname{Spc}} {\mathsf{T}}^c$ is noetherian is not necessary, but the situation is significantly more complicated without this assumption. If the spectrum is not noetherian then one can not necessarily define a tensor-idempotent, as in Definition~\ref{defn_gen_ptfunctors2}, for every point. However, the main ideas, as introduced in \cite{BaRickard} and discussed below, do work to some extent without the noetherian hypotheses and as shown in \cite{StevensonAbsFlat} one always has enough information to recover the supports of compact objects via the support of Definition~\ref{defn_bigsupport}.
\end{aside}

We now introduce the objects which allow us to extend the support defined in the first section for objects of ${\mathsf{T}}^c$ to arbitrary objects of ${\mathsf{T}}$. The construction was motivated by Rickard's work in modular representation theory \cite{Rickardidempotent} and the work of Hovey, Palmieri, and Strickland \cite{HPS} on the correct axiomatic framework in which to perform such constructions. 

We produce the objects we desire, named \emph{Rickard idempotents}, via the following key construction based on certain smashing localisations. This result is now somewhat standard, but we include some details. Further information and references can be found in \cite{BaRickard}.

\begin{thm}
Let ${\mathsf{T}}$ be a rigidly-compactly generated tensor triangulated category, $S{\subseteq} {\mathsf{T}}^c$ a set of compact objects, and set ${\mathsf{S}} = {\operatorname{loc}}^\otimes(S)$. Consider the corresponding smashing localisation sequence
\begin{displaymath}
\xymatrix{
{\mathsf{S}} \ar[r]<0.5ex>^-{i_*} \ar@{<-}[r]<-0.5ex>_-{i^!} & {\mathsf{T}} \ar[r]<0.5ex>^-{j^*} \ar@{<-}[r]<-0.5ex>_-{j_*} & {\mathsf{S}}^\perp
