The support defined above satisfies the following properties.
\begin{itemize}
\item[$(a)$] The two notions of support coincide for any compact object of ${\mathsf{T}}$.
\item[$(b)$] For any set-indexed family of objects $\{X_\lambda\; \vert \; \lambda \in \Lambda\}$ we have
\begin{displaymath}
{\operatorname{supp}} (\coprod_{\lambda \in \Lambda} X_\lambda) = \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} {\operatorname{supp}} X_\lambda.
\end{displaymath}
\item[$(c)$] For every $X\in {\mathsf{T}}$ ${\operatorname{supp}}({\Sigma} X) = {\operatorname{supp}}(X)$.
\item[$(d)$] Given a distinguished triangle $X {\longrightarrow} Y {\longrightarrow} Z {\longrightarrow}$ in ${\mathsf{T}}$ we have
\begin{displaymath}
{\operatorname{supp}}(Y) {\subseteq} {\operatorname{supp}}(X) \cup {\operatorname{supp}}(Z).
\end{displaymath}
\item[$(e)$] For any $X,Y \in {\mathsf{T}}$ we have ${\operatorname{supp}}(X\otimes Y){\subseteq} {\operatorname{supp}}(X)\cap {\operatorname{supp}}(Y)$.
