{\operatorname{hocolim}}_I \mathit{\Gamma}_{\mathcal{V}_i}\mathbf{1} {\longrightarrow} \mathit{\Gamma}_\mathcal{V}\mathbf{1} {\longrightarrow} Z {\longrightarrow} {\Sigma} {\operatorname{hocolim}}_I \mathit{\Gamma}_{\mathcal{V}_i}\mathbf{1}.
\end{displaymath}

In order to prove the lemma it is sufficient to show that $Z$ is isomorphic to the zero object in ${\mathsf{T}}$. If this is the case then the first map in the above triangle is the desired isomorphism.


The argument given in \cite{BousfieldBAS} can be extended to prove that localising subcategories are closed under homotopy colimits and so this triangle consists of objects of $\mathit{\Gamma}_\mathcal{V}{\mathsf{T}}$. By definition $\mathit{\Gamma}_\mathcal{V}{\mathsf{T}}$ is the full subcategory of ${\mathsf{T}}$ generated by those objects of ${\mathsf{T}}^c$ whose support is contained in $\mathcal{V}$. Thus $Z{\cong} 0$ if and only if for each compact object $t$ with ${\operatorname{supp}} t {\subseteq} \mathcal{V}$ we have ${\operatorname{Hom}}(t,Z) = 0$. We note there is no ambiguity here as by Proposition~\ref{prop_supp_prop} the two notions of support, that of \cite{BaSpec} and \cite{BaRickard}, agree for compact objects. In particular, the support of any compact object is closed.

